Simple idea is to maintain two arrays for values and increments. Keep a counter to track the current `currInd`.  We lazily transfer the `inc` down the stack when `pop` takes place. 

- On a `push` just initialize the `currInd`. Note we just overwrite entries.
- On a `pop` transfer the `inc` value to `currInd-1`. This way we transfer `inc` to the bottom entries. Also the actual value in the stack is `val`+`inc` value.
- On an `increment` just update the `kth` index. 

So if we see two increments for `(ind, val)` -> `(3,10)` and `(5,15)` we will maintain 15 and 10 at right indices. Once pop occurs at index 5 we will transfer 15 to index 4, and on subsequent pop the inc value becomes `10+15=25` at index 3.   

```
class CustomStack {

    int currInd = -1;
    int valStack[];
    int incStack[];
    int maxLen;
    public CustomStack(int maxSize) {
        valStack = new int[maxSize];
        incStack = new int[maxSize];
        maxLen = maxSize;
    }

    public void push(int x) {
        if (currInd+1 != maxLen) {
            valStack[currInd+1] = x;
            incStack[currInd+1] = 0;
            currInd++;
        }
    }

    public int pop() {
        if (currInd == -1) {
            return -1;
        }
        int val = valStack[currInd]+incStack[currInd];
        if (currInd > 0) {
            incStack[currInd-1] += incStack[currInd];
        }
        currInd--;    
        return val;
    }

    public void increment(int k, int val) {
        if (currInd == -1) {
            return;
        }
        int ind = Math.min(currInd, k-1);
        incStack[ind] += val;
    }
}

