solutions.content:
We can use a Stack to hold numbers, which is easy. The trick is how do we maintain the incremented values on each k? Using an array [0, 1, ..., maxSize] will denote that arr[i] represents the increment applied to all element from stack[0, ..., i] or from the bottom element to the ith element. Using an array is best because we can access the increment k from any position or index in O(1) time.

How to handle increment(k, val) ?
We can simply increment arr[k] += val, this way even if increment(k, val) is called repeatedly with the same k, the amount is always added up. The only case to be aware of is whether or not ```K > stack.size()``` because this may cause an index out of bounds exception.

How to handle pop?
For the case where stack is empty, return -1.
Otherwise get the increment amount we must apply to the popped value, by calling ```int amount = arr[stack.size()]```. This access provides the amount to increment for the popped value and all values below it in the stack. Then erase the increment being applied to the popped value from the arr like so: ```arr[stack.size()] = 0```. Finally, we want to maintain that increment for all items in the stack so we add it to the previous index ```arr[stack.size() - 1] += amount```. Finally just ```stack.pop() + amount``` to get the next value incremented.

The only edge case to worry about is when k > maxSize which would be out of bounds.
```
class CustomStack {

    Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();
    int[] additions;
    int maxSize;

    public CustomStack(int maxSize) {
        this.maxSize = maxSize;
        this.additions = new int[maxSize + 1];
    }

    public void push(int x) {
        // edge case: stack is full at maxSize
        if (stack.size() == maxSize)
            return;
        // push val into stack
        stack.push(x);
    }

    public int pop() {
        // edge case: stack is empty
        if (stack.isEmpty())
            return -1;

        // get addition amount for next num and erase it from arr
        int amount = additions[stack.size()];
        additions[stack.size()] = 0;

        // add amount to item below next val
        additions[stack.size() - 1] += amount;

        return stack.pop() + amount;
    }

    public void increment(int k, int val) {
        // add val to kth index
        additions[Math.min(k, stack.size())] += val;
    }
}```

