solutions.content:
My `JAVA` solution using an array to represent the stack.

`Adding` elements to the stack : 
* We add elements in our stack array from left to right (index 0 to MAX - 1).
* Here index is the leftmost free position in stack array.

`Removing` elements from the stack : 
* We remove elements from our stack array from right to left (index MAX - 1 to 0).
* Here index is the rightmost element in stack array.

`Increment` elements last k elements by value :
* So we have to add value to the elements from index 0 to endPosition.
* `endPosition =  Math.min(k - 1, index - 1).`
* Add value to endPosition(it will mean that we have to add value from index 0 to endPosition).
* Now during removal of an element from stack array, we pass this removed index value to the previous element in stack.

```
class CustomStack {
    int[] stack;
    int[] increment;
    int MAX;
    int index = 0;
    public CustomStack(int maxSize) {
        MAX = maxSize;
        stack = new int[MAX];
        increment = new int[MAX];
    }

    public void push(int x) {
        if (index == MAX) {
            return;
        }
        stack[index] = x;
        index++;
    }

    public int pop() {
        if (index == 0) {
            return -1;
        }
        if (index > 1) {
            increment[index - 2] += increment[index - 1];
        }
        index--;
        int sum = stack[index] + increment[index];
        increment[index] = 0;
        return sum;
    }

    public void increment(int k, int val) {
        if (index == 0) {
            return;
        }
        int endPosition = Math.min(k - 1, index - 1);
        increment[endPosition] += val;
    }
}

