solutions.content:
I saw a few JavaScript solutions that were using .pop() and .push(). While they are available methods that really doesn't show that someone in JavaScript actually knows how .push() and .pop() work. 

When you attempt to write a solution without those functions you'll learn more about how arrays work behind the scenes:

Here's more info:
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/27386264/how-does-the-javascript-array-push-code-work-internally

You'll note that when I add an element in .push(), I'm not having to adjust the .length property. Whereas when I delete an element manually I must update it. Run this in debug mode in your IDE to see why and what happens ;) It is rather interesting.

```
var CustomStack = function(maxSize) {
    this.maxSize = maxSize;
    this.stack = [];
};

/**
 * @param {number} x
 * @return {void}
 */
CustomStack.prototype.push = function(x) {
    if(this.stack.length < this.maxSize) {
        this.stack[this.stack.length] = x;
    }
};

/**
 * @return {number}
 */
CustomStack.prototype.pop = function() {
    if(this.stack.length > 0) {
        const retVal = this.stack[this.stack.length - 1];
        delete this.stack[this.stack.length - 1];
        this.stack.length = this.stack.length - 1;
        return retVal;
    } else {
        return -1;
    }
};

/**
 * @param {number} k
 * @param {number} val
 * @return {void}
 */
CustomStack.prototype.increment = function(k, val) {
    for(let i = 0; i < k; i++) {
        if(this.stack[i]) this.stack[i] = this.stack[i] + val;
    }
};
```

