Brute force to check each substring to see if it is nice.

Use two 32-bit integers as bitmasks to keep track of the lowercase and uppercase alphabets seen in the substring.

If both values equal, then it means all characters in the substring have both their lower or upper cases counterparts present as well, so we can just take the substring as a candidate for the result.

Of course we'll still want to keep track of the longest and earliest beautiful substring as result.

Time complexity: `O(N^2)`
Space complexity: `O(1)`

```
class Solution {
public:
    std::string longestNiceSubstring(std::string s) {
        const auto N = s.size();

        std::string result;

        for ( size_t i = 0; i < N; ++i ) {
            int bitmaskLowerCase = 0;
            int bitmaskUpperCase = 0;

            for ( size_t j = i; j < N; ++j ) {
                char c = s[j];

                if ( c >= 'a' && c <= 'z' )
                    bitmaskLowerCase |= ( 1 << ( c - 'a' ) );

                if ( c >= 'A' && c <= 'Z' )
                    bitmaskUpperCase |= ( 1 << ( c - 'A' ) );

                if ( ( bitmaskLowerCase == bitmaskUpperCase ) && ( bitmaskLowerCase > 0 ) ) {
                    if ( (j-i+1) > result.size() )
                        result = s.substr(i, j-i+1);
                }
            }
        }

        return result;
    }
};
```

