solutions.content:
It's the expected quadratic brute force naive solution but uses a neat representation of both cases of of the whole alphabet using bitwise operations to still run fast on the small problem sizes that the judging code offers. This stuffs the same functionality that naively you'd pull in an unordered map/set for into a value that fits in a single processor register.

There is also an algorithmic tweak in that the outer loop terminates as soon as there are not enough characters left to form a nice substring as long as the longest seen so far.

```cpp
uint8_t longest_from(const string& s, const size_t start)
{
    // The "unordered_set" to record characters in the substring as we iterate over it:
	uint64_t flags = 0;
	size_t longest = 0;

    // We got lucky and the distance from A to z and the
	// punctuation padding the space between the cases is <= 64.
	for(auto i = start; i < s.length(); ++i){
		flags |= uint64_t(1u) << (s[i] -'A');
		if((flags & (uint64_t(1u)<<32u)-1) == (flags >> 32u)){
			longest = i - start + 1;
		}
	}
	return longest;
}


class Solution {
public:
    string longestNiceSubstring(const string& s)
    {   
        size_t longest_start = 0;
        size_t longest_len = 0;

        for(size_t i = 0; i < s.length(); ++i)
        {
            size_t pos_longest = longest_from(s, i);
            if(pos_longest > longest_len){
                longest_start = i;
                longest_len = pos_longest;
            }

            // End if we don't have enough characters left in the input to beat the longest so far:
            if(longest_len >= s.length() - i) break;
        }
        return s.substr(longest_start, longest_len);
    }
};
```

